Subject: [PATCH] fix: usability/accessibility pass on type scale + redesign
 comparison table
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Type scale (styles.css):
- Contrast was already solid across the palette (verified with WCAG
  formulas: accent teal is 10.8:1 on the page background, well above
  the 4.5:1 AA threshold) — the actual problem was pure size. 22 rules
  sat at exactly 12px against a 14px body base, with a long tail down
  to 10/10.5/11/11.5px for things like module-picker stat labels
  (.mg i), the mining/combat stat captions (.kstat i), and slot
  rationale text (.slot-why, which also used the lower-contrast
  --accent-dim at small size — the likely source of the 'small teal
  text' complaint).
- Raised every sub-12px rule to 12px+ (module picker labels, badges,
  flags), and bumped ~10 more 12px reading-content labels (card
  metadata, table headers, mod stats) to 12.5px.
- h2/h3 and the Fitting screen's rack-section headers (accent teal,
  uppercase, heavily tracked) bumped from 12px/13px with 0.12-0.16em
  tracking down to 0.1em — tight tracking on small uppercase teal text
  was fighting legibility as much as size was.

Comparison table (styles.css + CompareView.tsx):
- table-layout: fixed with explicit column widths (220px label / 148px
  per ship) instead of width: 100% — a 4-ship comparison no longer
  stretches to the full page width (1368px -> 812px measured), it sizes
  to its actual content.
- Vertical dividers between columns (border-left) so a row's values
  don't blur together horizontally — this was the main complaint.
- Alternating row tint for horizontal scannability, implemered as an
  explicit data-row-alt class from CompareView.tsx rather than CSS
  nth-child (section header rows interrupt the sequence irregularly,
  so nth-child striped inconsistently across section boundaries).
- Ship name headers now wrap within their fixed column instead of
  forcing the column wider via white-space: nowrap.
- 'Best' cell highlight kept and given a proper background tint
  instead of relying on text color alone.
